# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: 1799-virginia-gubernatorial-election
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:1799-virginia-gubernatorial-election/1776-virginia-gubernatorial-election] A gubernatorial election was held in Virginia on June 29, 1776.
[src:1799-virginia-gubernatorial-election/1776-virginia-gubernatorial-election] The delegate from Hanover County Patrick Henry defeated Thomas Nelson Jr. and John Page.
[src:1799-virginia-gubernatorial-election/1776-virginia-gubernatorial-election] The election took place forty-five days after the adoption of the Lee Resolution by the Fifth Virginia Convention declaring the independence of the United Colonies from Great Britain.
[src:1799-virginia-gubernatorial-election/1776-virginia-gubernatorial-election] The Constitution of Virginia had been adopted by the convention the same day and went into effect immediately.
[src:1799-virginia-gubernatorial-election/1776-virginia-gubernatorial-election] The new constitution called for the governor of Virginia to be elected by the votes of the Virginia General Assembly meeting in joint session.
[src:1799-virginia-gubernatorial-election/1776-virginia-gubernatorial-election] The Virginia Convention, as the provisional legislature of the commonwealth, performed this function in the election of 1776.
[src:1799-virginia-gubernatorial-election/1776-virginia-gubernatorial-election] Prior to 1830, the governor served a term of one year, renewable no more than three times in a seven-year period.
[src:1799-virginia-gubernatorial-election/1776-virginia-gubernatorial-election] Henry was reelected four times: twice consecutively in 1777 and 1778, and again in 1784 and 1785, to serve a total of five consecutive terms in office.
[src:1799-virginia-gubernatorial-election/1776-virginia-gubernatorial-election] The Fifth Virginia Convention convened in Williamsburg on May 6, 1776, amidst increasingly widespread support for independence among the Patriots who supported the American Revolution.
[src:1799-virginia-gubernatorial-election/1776-virginia-gubernatorial-election] On May 15, 1776, the convention approved a resolution instructing Virginia's delegates in the Second Continental Congress to support a formal declaration of independence absolving the Thirteen Colonies from their allegiance to the British Empire.
[src:1799-virginia-gubernatorial-election/1776-virginia-gubernatorial-election] Congress voted to adopt the Lee Resolution on July 2, precipitating passage of the United States Declaration of Independence.
[src:1799-virginia-gubernatorial-election/1776-virginia-gubernatorial-election] While Congress debated independence, the Virginia Convention took action to establish the foundations for an independent commonwealth.
[src:1799-virginia-gubernatorial-election/1776-virginia-gubernatorial-election] A Declaration of Rights was introduced in the convention on May 27 and adopted on June 12; on June 29, the delegates voted unanimously to adopt the proposed Constitution of Virginia.
[src:1799-virginia-gubernatorial-election/1776-virginia-gubernatorial-election] With the Constitution now in place, elections for governor and Attorney General proceeded immediately.
[src:1799-virginia-gubernatorial-election/1776-virginia-gubernatorial-election] The Constitution of 1776 called for the governor and other executive officers to be elected by a joint session of the General Assembly, with a majority of votes cast necessary to elect the governor.
[src:1799-virginia-gubernatorial-election/1776-virginia-gubernatorial-election] The governor was elected for a term of one year and limited to three terms in a seven-year period.
[src:1799-virginia-gubernatorial-election/1776-virginia-gubernatorial-election] With the first General Assembly yet unelected, the Virginia Convention carried out the election of the first governor and Attorney General.
[src:1799-virginia-gubernatorial-election/1776-virginia-gubernatorial-election] The election was conducted by secret ballot; in all, 106 delegates to the Virginia Convention cast votes for governor.
[src:1799-virginia-gubernatorial-election/1776-virginia-gubernatorial-election] The Virginia Convention elected Henry by a majority of 60 electoral votes to 45 for his nearest competitor, Thomas Nelson.
[src:1799-virginia-gubernatorial-election/1776-virginia-gubernatorial-election] George Wythe, James Madison, Bartholomew Dandridge, and William Roscoe Wilson Curl were appointed to inspect the ballots and inform Henry of his election.
[src:1799-virginia-gubernatorial-election/1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election] A gubernatorial election was scheduled to be held in Virginia on May 29, 1777.
[src:1799-virginia-gubernatorial-election/1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election] However, when the Virginia General Assembly met to conduct the election, the incumbent governor of Virginia Patrick Henry was the only candidate nominated.
[src:1799-virginia-gubernatorial-election/1777-virginia-gubernatorial-election] By a joint resolution of the Senate and House of Delegates, balloting was dispensed with and Henry was declared re-elected by acclamation.
[src:1799-virginia-gubernatorial-election/1778-virginia-gubernatorial-election] A gubernatorial election was scheduled to be held in Virginia on May 29, 1778.
[src:1799-virginia-gubernatorial-election/1779-virginia-gubernatorial-election] A gubernatorial election was held in Virginia on June 1, 1779.
[src:1799-virginia-gubernatorial-election/1779-virginia-gubernatorial-election] The delegate from Albemarle County Thomas Jefferson defeated the president of the Council of State John Page.
[src:1799-virginia-gubernatorial-election/1779-virginia-gubernatorial-election] The incumbent governor of Virginia Patrick Henry was ineligible for re-election due to term limits established by the Constitution of Virginia.
[src:1799-virginia-gubernatorial-election/1779-virginia-gubernatorial-election] The election was conducted by the Virginia General Assembly in joint session.
[src:1799-virginia-gubernatorial-election/1779-virginia-gubernatorial-election] No candidate had a majority after the first count, requiring a second ballot between the two top-finishers.
[src:1799-virginia-gubernatorial-election/1780-virginia-gubernatorial-election] A gubernatorial election was held in Virginia on June 2, 1780.
[src:1799-virginia-gubernatorial-election/1780-virginia-gubernatorial-election] The incumbent governor of Virginia Thomas Jefferson was re-elected.
[src:1799-virginia-gubernatorial-election/1780-virginia-gubernatorial-election] The Senate and the House of Delegates met separately on June 1 to nominate candidates for governor; more than one nomination was made, requiring a vote of the Virginia General Assembly.
[src:1799-virginia-gubernatorial-election/1780-virginia-gubernatorial-election] When the Assembly met in joint session the following day, Jefferson was selected by the majority of members on the first ballot, although the names of the other candidates and the votes tallied were not recorded.
[src:1799-virginia-gubernatorial-election/1782-virginia-gubernatorial-election] A gubernatorial election was held in Virginia on November 20, 1782.
[src:1799-virginia-gubernatorial-election/1782-virginia-gubernatorial-election] The incumbent governor of Virginia Benjamin Harrison V was re-elected.
[src:1799-virginia-gubernatorial-election/1782-virginia-gubernatorial-election] The House of Delegates met on November 19 to make nominations for governor and other offices, which the Senate accepted without amendment; the rule disqualifying votes for candidates other than those nominated was repealed prior to the balloting.
[src:1799-virginia-gubernatorial-election/1782-virginia-gubernatorial-election] Harrison was selected by a majority of members on the first ballot; the official record of the proceedings does not include the names or tallied votes for any other candidates.
[src:1799-virginia-gubernatorial-election/1783-virginia-gubernatorial-election] A gubernatorial election was held in Virginia on November 27, 1783.
[src:1799-virginia-gubernatorial-election/1783-virginia-gubernatorial-election] The House of Delegates met on November 26 to make nominations for governor and other offices, which the Senate accepted without amendment.
[src:1799-virginia-gubernatorial-election/1783-virginia-gubernatorial-election] On the day of the election, Harrison was selected by a majority of members on the first ballot; the official record of the proceedings does not include the names or tallied votes for any other candidates.
[src:1799-virginia-gubernatorial-election/1799-virginia-gubernatorial-election] A gubernatorial election was held in Virginia on December 6, 1799.
[src:1799-virginia-gubernatorial-election/1799-virginia-gubernatorial-election] The Democratic-Republican former U.S. minister to France James Monroe defeated the Federalist member of the Virginia House of Delegates from Botetourt County James Breckinridge.
[src:1799-virginia-gubernatorial-election/1799-virginia-gubernatorial-election] Monroe had been a possible candidate for governor in 1797, but declined to challenge the incumbent governor of Virginia James Wood.
[src:1799-virginia-gubernatorial-election/1799-virginia-gubernatorial-election] With Wood ineligible for re-election due to term limits established by the Constitution of Virginia, the state's Democratic-Republican leaders nominated Monroe to succeed the retiring incumbent.
[src:1799-virginia-gubernatorial-election/1799-virginia-gubernatorial-election] The nomination was a public vote of confidence in Monroe, who was known for his strong opposition to the national Adams Administration and the hated Alien and Sedition Acts.
[src:1799-virginia-gubernatorial-election/1799-virginia-gubernatorial-election] Democratic-Republicans were equally interested in the significance of the gubernatorial race for the 1800 United States presidential election in Virginia.
[src:1799-virginia-gubernatorial-election/1799-virginia-gubernatorial-election] As governor, Monroe, a close ally of Thomas Jefferson, would be positioned to promote the success of the Democratic-Republican national ticket and ensure friendly administration of the election.
[src:1799-virginia-gubernatorial-election/1799-virginia-gubernatorial-election] The election attracted little comment from the press, despite Federalist efforts to disparage Monroe's diplomatic record.
[src:1799-virginia-gubernatorial-election/1799-virginia-gubernatorial-election] The support of the Democratic-Republican leaders in the highly-partisan, elite-led political culture of eighteenth century Virginia made Monroe's election a forgone conclusion.
[src:1799-virginia-gubernatorial-election/1799-virginia-gubernatorial-election] Monroe was elected with a majority on the first ballot.
